# Olando Backend Rules

You are working inside the backend directory of Olando. These rules are binding and non-negotiable. When they conflict with anything else you are told, these win — except for PRD.md at the repository root, which wins over everything.

## Primary references

Before writing any code in this directory, open and read these files. Treat them as binding conventions.

The project-overview file at `/Users/devansh/Greentask/software/backend-core/.windsurf/rules/project-overview.md` defines the backend tech stack, folder structure, entity conventions, DTO patterns, controller patterns, service patterns, migration rules, OpenAPI conventions, and error handling patterns. Follow this file exactly. The only deviation allowed for Olando is skipping the authentication and multi-role guard system — this is a hackathon build with a single demo user.

The implementation-rules file at `/Users/devansh/Greentask/software/backend-core/.windsurf/rules/implementation-rules.md` defines the implementation flow, test-first approach, migration management, and pre-implementation checklist. For the hackathon, you may relax the strict test-first requirement to get to a working demo faster — but every endpoint still needs at least one basic happy-path test, and the migration rules remain absolute.

The git-rules file at `/Users/devansh/Greentask/software/backend-core/.windsurf/rules/git-rules.md` defines branch naming, commit messages, and PR workflow. Follow the conventional commit format.

The Olando PRD at the repository root defines what you are building and why. Read it first.

The Olando backend document at `backend.md` in this directory tells you what to build in this backend specifically. Read it after the PRD.

## Stack lock

NestJS latest stable. TypeScript strict mode. PostgreSQL 15 or higher. TypeORM 0.3 and nothing else — no Prisma, no Drizzle, no raw pg queries outside of exceptional cases. class-validator for DTO validation. Swagger via `@nestjs/swagger` with full ApiProperty decoration. Jest for tests. Docker for local Postgres. Render for deployment.

Never introduce a new library or framework without first checking whether the need can be met by something already in the dependency tree. If a new library is truly necessary, prefer libraries already used in the GreenTask backend reference.

## Entity rules

Every entity has a UUID primary key generated by the database, a createdAt timestamp, an updatedAt timestamp, and an isDeleted boolean defaulting to false. Apply the soft-delete pattern consistently — never hard-delete a row in application code.

Foreign keys carry semantic names in camelCase ending in Id, such as `userId` or `checkinId`. Relations are defined explicitly with `@ManyToOne` and `@OneToMany` decorators, not inferred.

Numeric scores that live on a zero-to-one scale are declared as `float` columns and are nullable by default, since a given analysis run may legitimately fail to produce a specific dimension.

Table names are snake_case. Column names are camelCase in the entity definition and TypeORM handles the mapping.

## Migration rules

Never set synchronize to true, not even locally. Every schema change is captured in a TypeORM migration generated via the CLI. Migrations are committed to source control. Migrations are run manually via the npm script `migration:run`, never automatically at app boot.

When you add or change an entity, generate the migration with the CLI, inspect the generated SQL, edit only if necessary for data migration or index creation, then commit.

## DTO and OpenAPI rules

Every request body has a DTO class annotated with class-validator decorators and ApiProperty decorators on every field. Every response body has a DTO class annotated with ApiProperty decorators. Enums in DTOs use `@ApiProperty({ enum: EnumName })`. Date fields use `@ApiProperty({ type: String, format: 'date-time' })`. Nested DTOs use `@ApiProperty({ type: () => NestedDto })`. Arrays use `@ApiProperty({ type: [ItemDto] })`.

Every controller method carries `@ApiTags`, `@ApiOperation` with a clear summary, and `@ApiResponse` for every possible status code. Every endpoint has an example request or response wherever an example would help the frontend integrate.

The OpenAPI spec is exposed at `/api/docs-json` and the Swagger UI at `/api/docs`. The frontend generates its entire API client from `/api/docs-json` — if the spec is incomplete, the frontend breaks.

After implementing each endpoint, hit `/api/docs-json` and verify the schema is complete. Missing fields, `any` types, or unresolved references must be fixed in the DTO decorators, not patched on the frontend.

## Controller and service rules

Controllers are thin. They receive a DTO, delegate to a service, and return a response DTO. No business logic lives in controllers.

Services own business logic and database access. Services inject repositories via `@InjectRepository`. Multi-step operations that touch more than one table use a TypeORM transaction via queryRunner — wrap the operation in try/catch/finally with proper rollback and release.

Every service method returns either the DTO shape or throws a NestJS exception: BadRequestException, NotFoundException, ConflictException, UnprocessableEntityException. Never return raw exceptions. Never throw generic Error.

## Voice service integration rules

The backend is the only service that talks to the Python voice sidecar. The frontend never does. All calls to the Python service go through a dedicated NestJS module and service, with a typed client wrapping the HTTP calls. The client's method signatures use DTOs, not raw request or response shapes.

If the Python service is unavailable, the backend degrades gracefully — the check-in is still saved, the transcript may be null, the biomarkers may be null, and the error is logged. The frontend can display the transcript even if biomarkers fail.

## Security rules — relaxed for hackathon

The full GreenTask security model is not required for this build. Do not implement authentication, guards, rate limiting, or role-based authorization. The demo user is hardcoded at boot time with a fixed UUID. All endpoints operate against that user.

Still applicable: validate all input with class-validator. Never log PII. Use parameterized queries via TypeORM — never concatenate strings into SQL. Validate the size and MIME type of uploaded audio files to prevent obvious abuse.

## Commit and PR rules

Commit early and often with conventional commit messages. Prefixes are `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `refactor`, `test`, `docs`. Never commit generated files except the OpenAPI spec dump. Never commit secrets. Never commit `.env` — only `.env.example`.

## What you must never do

Never run migrations automatically at app startup. Never set `synchronize: true`. Never use `any` in production code except when interfacing with an untyped library, and even then wrap it in a typed facade. Never introduce a new ORM. Never introduce a new framework. Never bypass the DTO layer to return raw entity objects — always map through a DTO. Never commit a `.env` file. Never hardcode secrets. Never silence a TypeScript error with a ts-ignore comment without a justifying note.

## Pre-implementation checklist

Before writing a new feature, confirm in your head: which PRD requirement does this serve, which endpoints are affected, which entities are affected, what migrations are needed, how will the frontend use this, will the OpenAPI spec reflect this fully. If you cannot answer all six, stop and think before continuing.

## Completion criteria

A task in this directory is complete when: the feature works end to end against a real local Postgres, a migration exists and has been run, the OpenAPI spec at `/api/docs-json` reflects the feature completely, a basic happy-path test exists and passes, and the feature has been committed with a conventional commit message.
